Heliomycin  (resistomycin,  1,  Fig.  (1)),  a  metabolite  produced  var.  heliomycini  and  Streptomyces  resistomycificus  has  been  known  since  1950s  to  demonstrate  a  variety  of  valuable  activities  including  antimicrobial,  antifungal,  antiviral  [1,  2]. This antibiotic has been used in the former Soviet Union  as  a  pharmaceutical  substance  of  an  aerosol  or  ointment  drug formulations to treat skin infections. However, an ex- tremely  low  solubility  of  1  in  aqueous  media  and  in  the  majority of organic solvents limited its medical application  [3,  4].  Thus,  due  to  a  high  practical  potential  and  a  poor  solubility  of  1,  new  routes  of  structural  modification  are  strongly required.

Although 1 has been discovered more than 60 years ago,  there are only few reports on its chemical modifications [5- 7]. 4-Aminomethyl derivatives of 1 were not previously de- scribed and investigated; we, therefore, set out to explore this  chemotype of semi-synthetic antibiotics.  Our  recent  invention  [8]  described  the  preparation  of  4- aminomethyl derivatives of 1 with an improved solubility in  pharmaceutically acceptable solvents and antitumor prospec- tive. However, an extremely low  solubility in aqueous media and in the majority of organic solvents limits its practical application.  Objective:  Due  to  a  high  practical  potential  of  heliomycin,  new  routes  of  structural  modification  are  strongly required to improve its solubility.  Conclusion: The patent claims a series of 4-aminomethyl derivatives of heliomycin as well as a phar- maceutical composition based on it. Application of Mannich aminomethylation allowed to diversify the  structure of initial antibiotic and to obtain the derivatives with significantly improved water solubility  and a potent antiproliferative efficacy.   2212-3970/18 $58.00+.00  Recent Patents on Anti-Cancer Drug Discovery, 2018, 13, 469-472  Fig. (1). One method that illustrates the possibility of preparing the  structures 2 is based on Mannich aminomethylation. Accord- ingly, 1 was treated with stable iminium salts (Eschenmoser's  reagent) in DMF to give 2a up to 97% yield (Fig. (3), Method  1).  Derivatives  2b-q  were  prepared  using  linear  or  cyclic  amines and formaldehyde in an appropriate solvent (Fig. (3),  Method  2).  If  aminomethylation  of  1  was  performed  in  the  presence of polyfunctional amines, the protective groups were  used to ensure selectivity, followed by their removal.  Fig. (3). Synthesis of 4-aminomethyl derivatives 2a-q.  The performed chemical modifications of 1 significantly  increased  the  solubility  of  new  derivatives  (general  formula  2)  in  aqueous  and  organic  media.  The  following  examples  illustrate important issues of the invention.

Example  1.  4-((dimethylamino)methyl)heliomycin-hydro-  chloride (2a). A mixture of heliomycin (1, 50mg, 0.13mmol)  and chloride of N,N-dimethyl(methylene)ammonium (50mg,  0.54mmol) was dissolved in DMF (5ml) and heated for 3h at  75ºC,  then  cooled  to  room  temperature  and  diluted  with  di- ethyl  ether  (20ml).  The  resulted  precipitate  was  filtered  off,  washed  with  diethyl  ether  (15ml),  dried  and  re-precipitated  from water with acetone. Yield 55mg (97%), orange powder,  mp  >  250ºC. Example  3.  Antiproliferative  activity  of  2a-q.  The  anti- proliferative activity of 2a-q was tested on a panel of mam- malian  cell  lines  including  mouse  L1210  lymphocytic  leu- kemia,  human  T-lymphocytes  CEM,  cervical  carcinoma  HeLa,  colon  adenocarcinoma  HCT116  and  its  subline  HCT116p53KO  (p53  deleted),  chronic  myeloid  leukemia  K562, its multidrug resistant K562/4 subline (overexpression  of P-glycoprotein), and HMEC-1 endothelial cells. IC50 val- ues were determined in an MTT-test.  Table 1 shows that 2a-q inhibited tumor cell proliferation  at submicromolar to micromolar concentrations. Compounds  2c,  2e,  2i,  2l  and  2o  demonstrated  a  superior  cytotoxic  po- tency  against  all  tested  cell  lines,  with  IC50  values  close  to  the  parent  1.  The  majority  of  new  derivatives  blocked  the  growth  of  both  wild-type  cell  lines  and  their  drug-resistant  counterparts.  Importantly,  for  2a,  2b,  2g  and  2q,  the  thera- peutic ‘window’ between colon carcinoma HCT116 and non- malignant  HMEC-1  cell  lines  was  substantial  (Table  1).  In  contrast, 2e, 2i, 2l and 2o were similarly cytotoxic for tumor  and non-malignant cell lines.  Semi-synthetic Derivatives of Heliomycin  Values are data of the MTT test (mean ± S.D.; 3 experiments) after 72 h incubation. N.t., not tested.

The present patent claims a series of 4-aminomethyl de- rivatives of the natural antibiotic 1 (compounds 2) as well as  a  pharmaceutical  composition  based  on  2.  Application  of  Mannich aminomethylation allowed to diversify the structure  of 1 and to obtain the derivatives with significantly improved  water  solubility  and  a  potent  antiproliferative  efficacy.  Fea- tures of the proposed mechanism of antiproliferative activity  are discussed in the full paper [9].
